SIMPLE: interlude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interlude
<hw>In`ter*lude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>enterlude</ets>, LL. <ets>interludium</ets>; LL. <ets>inter</ets>
between + <ets>ludus</ets> play, fr. <ets>ludere</ets> to play: cf. F.
<ets>interlude</ets>. See <er>Ludicrous</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A short entertainment exhibited on the stage between
the acts of a play, or between the play and the afterpiece, to relieve
the tedium of waiting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dreams are but <qex>interludes</qex>, which fancy makes⟦br⟧
When monarch reason sleeps.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A form of English drama or play, usually short,
merry, and farcical, which succeeded the Moralities or Moral Plays in
the transition to the romantic or Elizabethan drama.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A short piece of instrumental
music played between the parts of a song or cantata, or the acts of a
drama; especially, in church music, a short passage played by the
organist between the stanzas of a hymn, or in German chorals after each
line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Any intervening period of
time, space, etc.; a pause between phases of an activity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interluded</ent>⟦br⟧
